  "response_text": "The commercial opens above a sunny beach, looking straight down at pale sand, foamy surf, and several colorful umbrellas casting round shadows. A lone person walks near the waterline, while beach towels and umbrellas are spread below. On the sand beside a bright pink towel, a pair of bare feet presses and buries the toes into a little mound of sand. An orange flying disc lies nearby, and another person’s legs approach in the background, making the toe-hiding gesture feel deliberate.\n\nThe setting shifts to a bright, tidy living room with a large brown leather sofa, a coffee table, and a white kitchen in the background. An adult man in a green T-shirt and rolled-up jeans sits sideways on the couch with his knees bent. A white bulldog lies beside him, droopy-faced, on the same sofa cushion. As another adult, partly visible at the left edge, stands nearby in jeans and flip-flops, the man slides his bare feet back toward the dog and the sofa cushions, tucking them out of easy view.\n\nBy a swimming pool, the view is from someone reclining on a white slatted lounge chair. Their bare feet point toward the pool, then curl and pull inward under the chair’s front slats as a person in black flip-flops walks past on the brick pool deck. In a garden, a bare foot in a dark flip-flop steps onto a coiled green hose lying in the grass, pressing the toes down among the loops. In a yoga or exercise studio, a bare foot beside a green mat nudges the edge of a blue mat upward and slips the toes underneath it, again hiding them.\n\nA clean white background introduces the product imagery. A pair of bare feet rests on the white surface, with small on-screen text along the bottom reading, “Prescription KERYDIN (tavaborole) is FDA-approved,” and the Kerydin logo at the lower right. A hand brings in a small applicator dropper and lowers it toward a big toenail, positioning the tip as if to apply liquid medication. The view then moves very close to the toenails; on one large toenail, the words “TOENAIL FUNGUS” appear written in rough, dark letters. At the bottom, small text explains that Kerydin drops are used once daily for 48 weeks on affected toenails only, and that it can take a year or more to grow a healthy toenail.\n\nBack on the beach, several adults lie on turquoise striped towels arranged like spokes in a circle, their feet pointing inward toward the center. Some are in swimsuits or light beach clothing, and the sand around them is textured with footprints. A white band across the bottom carries safety text: “KERYDIN may cause irritation at the treated site,” with the Kerydin logo on the right.\n\nThe scene changes to a yoga class in a warm orange-walled studio. Adults sit or stand on mats with their arms raised overhead. A bearded adult man in a gray shirt smiles slightly as he stretches, with other participants close beside him. The lower white band now lists common side effects, including skin peeling, ingrown toenail, redness, itching, and swelling. The focus drops to a row of bare feet lined up on green and blue yoga mats, the participants standing evenly spaced on a wooden floor while the same side-effect text remains visible.\n\nOutdoors again, at a sunny backyard gathering, the view stays low at foot level. Bare feet and flip-flopped feet cross a strip of green grass in front of a patio, flowerpots, and a grill. People in summer clothing move casually through the yard; one person in a rust-colored skirt steps forward in flat sandals, while others stand or pass in the background. The bottom text reads, “Individual results may vary,” with the Kerydin logo still at the lower right. Two people’s feet face each other on the grass, suggesting a social moment, with one person in dark pants and black flip-flops opposite the person in the skirt and sandals.\n\nThe yoga studio returns briefly. A man seated cross-legged on a green mat lifts one bare foot high near his head, holding the ankle with one hand, while a woman beside him sits upright on her mat in a calm pose. Shelves behind them hold rolled yoga mats in different colors. A small note at the bottom says, “See our ad in People,” alongside the Kerydin logo.\n\nNear the end, a pair of bare feet rests together under a white sheet on a bed. The toes are visible at first, nestled against the sheet, then the white bedding slides down and covers them completely, leaving only soft folds of fabric filling the screen. Over the white fabric, the Kerydin droplet logo appears, followed by a small bottle and applicator cap beside the product name. The final screen reads “Kerydin (tavaborole) topical solution, 5%,” with the product bottle on the left and the Kerydin name large in blue. At the bottom, the visible contact line says, “Visit www.TOETUCKER.com or call 1-844-KERYDIN for product information.”",
